On 10/15/2018 at 1000 hours EST CSXT personnel in the Gentilly Yard (New Orleans, LA) discovered UTLX632119, a residue tank car of Sodium Hydroxide Solution with the manway cover in the open position. The car was isolated and the shipper, SSC Industries was notified. Specialized Professional Services Inc (SPSI), a CSXT response contractor, responded and found the manway cover in the open position propped open with the manway swing bolts, the bottom outlet valve cap not installed, and the vapor line chain not attached to the plug. The issues were identified and corrective actions were communicated to the consignee, Covestro LLC, (Chad Blake 304-281-4864) as the consignee Covestro was listed as the emergency contact and they advised they would contact the shipper. SPSI secured the manway cover, BOV plug, and the vapor line plug chain.  The car was released.    NAR Cause Code: 200 – Manway Bolts/ Nuts less than tool tight  5(4+5+0) x (2+0) = 90 NARRI   New Orleans, LA – 10/15/18 –UTLX632119 – Sodium Hydroxide Solution

column168: At 12:48 PM on 10/3/18 a Veolia driver stopped for lunch at 80 Horizon Drive, Suwanee, GA.  Upon returning to the truck at approximately 1:31 PM, the driver noticed a spill of approximately  15'x1.5' wide from the front corner of the truck onto the parking lot.  The driver placed absorbent  pads to contain the spilled materials and immediately notified the Veolia Operations Manager.  The  driver then placed additional absorbent pads into the truck and applied them to the area adjacent to  the leaking 11G box.  ERLLC was dispatched to assist the driver with the cleanup and to help  repackage the material from the leaking IBC into 2 poly drums.  Upon completion of the cleanup and  repacking the Veolia driver proceeded to the Veolia facility.  The GA DNR hotline was notified of the  incident (report #87603).
column169: The Veolia Operations Manager met with the customer on 10/9/18 to review the incident. While  remediating the spill it was identified that the IBC was improperly filled with damaged/leaking liquid  containers.  The customer was trained on the proper usage of absorbent material when packaging waste materials in accordance with 49 CFR 173.12(b) and has since chosen to package all liquid containers into drums to alleviate any future occurrence.

column162: SENIOR VICE PRESIDENT OF TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE
column168: Leaking drums were discovered on trailer. Facility contacted Clean Harbors Field Services to Clean up and remove drums. FS employees put on proper PPE and found leaking drum. Drum was found to have a failed gasket. All other drums on the manifest were inspected and 2 more failed gaskets we found. All bad gaskets we replaced, drums were re closed, and torqued to manufacture's specification and shipped to final disposal destination. Employee who  loaded drums had checked torque on closure, and did not notice any leaking drums as employee loaded drums. All drums were hand loaded due to not having an available Forklift. The state of CT was notified per the regulations.
column169: Employee was retrained on drum inspection procedures.

column168: A Butler County sherriff  pulled our driver over around Leon, KS on HWY 400 while he was headed east.  The sherriff noticed material leaking from the valve box of our trailer.  Our driver was able to contain the rest of the leak by closing the valve.  The valve had opened and the secondary valve was not holding properly.  The valve box does have a containment area in the belly of the trailer that was full.  Approximately 50 gallons were in the trailer belly that we drained and put into another compartment.  This compartment had 200 gallons loaded in it, so we are estimating 150 gallons were spilled along the highway.  We sent a crew out to do clean up along the route the driver took.  It was fisrt noticed at the intersection of the south El Dorado truck route and highway 54 when our driver turned south.  There were no pooling areas of spills to clean up, there were just several areas along the highway where we could tell something had spilled and got on the roadway.  Our crew caught up to our driver and helped him with clean up of his trailer belly.  The crew then went back the same way to make sure no areas on the roadway needed clean up.  Our crew reported no such areas needed spill clean up.  The sherriff was also going to go back through the route to see if anything needed to be done.  This entire stretch of roadway from where the first notice of spillage was to where our driver pulled over was about 12 miles.
column169: We have since sent this trailer into the shop to be looked over and have all the valves checked and secondary valves worked on as well.  We are hoping the shop can determine what may have caused the failure, as this is not a normal occurrance.  Other options to help with this would be to install locking valve handles and valve outlet caps.

column168: Package was received at our shipping dock from a customer with a cockpit voice/data recorder(CVR) inside the package. The 90 day beacon on the CVR contains 1.75g lithium metal content so this was a lithium metal battery packaged in equipment shipment. Package had no markings that it was a dangerous goods/hazardous materials shipment. Our shipping department personnel unpackaged the unit and delivered the unit to our repair department. We notified the shipper they shipped a dangerous good without the proper labels and documentation and that they needed to remedy this in the future and that Universal Avionics was required to report the incident. There was no release.
column169: Our personnel have received training on recognizing hazardous materials arriving at our dock with issues and to notify management when an incident occurs. We provided additional training to recognize when a hazardous material arrives without the appropriate markings or documentation and no release and to immediately report it to management so we can capture all the appropriate information in order to report the incident. We have also notified customers and dealers through newsletters, a notice on our customer website and a service bulletin about reshipping this particular product for repairs and the need to ship as dangerous goods/hazardous material.

column168: Package was received at our shipping dock from a customer with a cockpit voice/data recorder(CVR) inside the package. The 90 day beacon on the CVR contains 1.75g lithium metal content so this was a lithium metal battery packaged in equipment shipment. Package had no markings that it was a dangerous goods/hazardous materials shipment. Our shipping department personnel unpackaged the unit and delivered the unit to our repair department. We notified the shipper they shipped a dangerous good without the proper labels and documentation and that they needed to remedy this in the future and that Universal Avionics was required to report the incident. There was no release. The package received was the same box we had originally sent out with the unit containing the lithium battery. This box originally went out with the correct DG labels and documentation. From the way it looks, our customer removed the DG labels from the box to ship as a non-dangerous goods shipment.

column168: During highway transit, (3) 5-gallon metal pails containing UN 1263 paint E-Z VINYL® WHITE SEALER 550 VOC released approximately 1 quart of material through the can's body after being crushed. The cause of damage is unknown. A total of (10) 5-gallon metal pails were crushed. 3 out 10 leaked. XPO Logistics terminal personnel found the spillage within the cardboard over-packaging box and on the their concrete dock after removing it from the trailer with a forklift. It is not believe the unloading process is the reason for the damage to the container and spillage.  XPO Logistics terminal personnel called Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) for guidance on how to properly handle the hazardous materials spillage. ERTS instructed them to take the 3 leaking containers and place into (1) 30-gallon metal drum and staged it their OS&D for proper disposal. Granular absorbents was used to soak up the spillage on the concrete dock and placed in the 30-gallon metal drum with the damaged/leaking original containers.

column168: An end dump container trailer operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was parked at a company owned facility located at 500 Independence Parkway, La Porte, Texas, USA. While conducting a routine vehicle pre-trip inspection, the driver noticed that rainwater collected overnight in the tarp covering of the trailer. In an attempt to expel the water from the tarp, the driver engaged the hydraulics to lift the trailer body to an elevated position, resulting in spillage of residue which was left inside the dump trailer from the previous driver. The driver immediately placed a containment pail under the rear door and contacted his home dispatcher to request a response crew. Upon notification, a response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, removed the released material and placed it into 55 gallon drums for proper disposal. The released material and contaminated soil were properly packaged for shipment to a proper disposal facility. A report was made to the Texas Commission on Environmental Quality, report number: 20184039.
column169: In order to prevent a recurrence, all drivers at the local Clean Harbors facility have been instructed to ensure that dump trailers are 100% empty before leaving a destination facility. The driver has been re-instructed to perform a comprehensive inspection of the container's body to identify any potential issues before transportation.

column168: On 10/17/2018 at 1455 hours EST personnel in the Montgomery Yard (Montgomery, AL) discovered WCHX30216, a loaded tank car of Acetone with a release coming from the base of the liquid line valve and a release coming from the connection point on a blind flange.. The car was isolated and the shipper, David Rogers, INEOS, was notified. Marion Environmental Inc (MEI), a CSXT response contractor, responded and liquid phase product leaking from the base of the liquid line valve at the pressure plate and liquid phase product leaking from the base of the blind flange at the pressure plate. The issues were identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, INEOS (David Rogers, 251-454-0913). MEI applied temporary protective barrier to secure the release and the shipper was contacted to have a certified mobile repair respond for repairs.  The car was placed on hold.  It is believed that the gasket connection is deteriorated but cannot be verified until MRU repairs are complete.      NAR Cause Code: 279 – Liquid Line Valve connection (mounting) flange gasket deteriorated   5(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80 NARRI   Montgomery, AL – 10/17/18 –WCHX30216 – Acetone

A HAZMAT PACKAGE FELL OFF AN IRREG TRAIN NEAR BAY 801 ON BOXLINE 4. MATT, A SUPERVISOR NOTICED A COUPLE MINUTES LATER THAT IT HAD BEGUN TO LEAK SO HE CALLED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS. WHEN I ARRIVED TO THE AREA, I UTILIZED MY DECISION TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSESS THE SITUATION. BECAUSE THE PACKAGE WAS CORROSIVE, I ALTERED MY PPE TO INCLUDE THE SILVER SHIELD INNER LINERS. I TESTED THE PH OF THE LIQUID FOUND IT TO BE APPROX 12. I CONTAINERIZED THE LEAKING PACKAGE INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY. I USED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZED THE LIQUID. I RETESTED THE PH TO ENSURE THAT IT WAS IN THE 6-9 NEUTRAL RANGE. THEN I ADDED CLAY-BASED ABSORBENT TO SOLIDIFY ANY REMAINING LIQUID. I SWEPT UP ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIALS ADDED IT TO THE SPILL TRAY. I THEN TOOK THE PACKAGE TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. WHEN I OPENED THE BOX, I SAW THAT ON OF THE CAPS HAD COME LOOSE THAT THE PRODUCT HAD SOILED ALL 4 BOTTLES.
WET PACKAGE WAS FOUND IN THE PACKAGE CAR TO BE UNLOADED AND EMPLOYEE NOTIFIED SUPERVISOR AND DESIGNATED RESPONDER WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE WET PACKAGE.

At 0250 ET, ERTS received a call from Santmyer Oil regarding a spill located in Cleveland, OH at the Regional Transit Authority. At 0205 ET, the driver was offloading a shipment of UN1993 Diesel Fuel (Hauls 7500 gallons) to the customer location, when the offload was finish and the hose was disconnected, approximately 20 gallons of fuel released to the concrete pad and a storm drain in the area. The driver immediately deployed a spill kit in his tractor to contain what he could. Driver inspected the storm drain with a flashlight and determined that the fuel reached the bottom of the storm drain but not the outflow pipe. The impacted absorbents and debris placed down were contained into a 5 gallon bucket and was taken back to his facility for disposal. The spill is located along an unnamed side street that runs against the RTA building and the spill is located approximately 200 feet off of the Lakewood Heights Blvd street intersection on a concrete pad. ERTS contacted HEPACO for a dispatch, ETA is 1 hour and 30 minutes. At 0600 ET, HEPACO personnel completed work. The Facility Manager for Cleveland Regional Transit Authority, Michael Pulleo arrived on site and confirmed that the storm sewer area had a cave in causing ground water to run through the drain. HEPACO personnel inspected the next drain, approximately 100-150’ away in the middle of Lakewood Blvd but it was bone dry. Per HEPACO personnel they saw a large amount of dirt in the storm drain that may have absorbed the diesel fuel released. There was no visible sheen on water in the storm drain. The initial caller reported the tanker was hauling approximately 7500 gallons of UN1993 fuel and the delivery was made to two underground 20,000 gallon tanks for the amount of 3500 gallons in Tank 1 and 4000 gallons in Tank 2 which adds up to the 7500 gallons leaving a small amount of product to release possibly 15-20 gallons. HEPACO personnel was able to apply granular absorbents and pads to the concrete area. All impacted absorbents and debris were collected and containerized for waste disposal. Team off site at 0620 ET.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: The loaded trailer involved in this incident was delivered by the shipper to the Neier terminal located in Indianapolis, IN.  On October 1, Neier's driver conducted his pre-trip inspection, including a visual inspection of cargo, and adjusted load securement prior to transportation.  At this time there was no indication of leaking containers.  After departing Indianapolis, he became aware of material dripping from the trailer in Butler County OH and immediately pulled over to assess the situation, distribute material absorbents and buckets, and contacted emergency services.  Neier contracted an emergency remediation service to inspect, diagnose, and clean up the equipment and stopping location.  Upon arrival, the remediation company discovered liquid material on the interior floor of the trailer, but was unable to identify the leaking container at that time.  Neier equipment and the remediation company were escorted off the emergency lane of the roadway to a nearby travel plaza where the leaking drum was identified.  The leaking drum had a bung located on the side, approximately 8" from the bottom where material was slowly seeping out.  The remediation company reported that it was difficult to identify the leaking container due to it's position among the other shipping containers.  The drum was overpacked and the trailer floor was cleaned again prior to further transportation.
column169: The shipper should select proper packaging for the materials offered for transportation and ensure they are securely closed.  The shipping containers should be loaded in a manner to prevent shifting during transportation.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: On 10/10/2018, at 0858 hours, personnel in the CSXT Curtis Bay Yard discovered LTCX 1947, a loaded tank car of Argon Refrigerated Liquid, leaking from mid mount protective  housing. The car was isolated and the shipper Praxair, Leo Catusor Praxair's representative, Maryland Department of the Environment, and the National Response Center were notified.  Local Praxair personnel were dispatched to the scene and found a non-reclosing pressure relief device disc ruptured. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Mr. Leo Catuso, phone 609-865-4380. Praxair personnel installed a new rupture disc. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.   Cause Code: 441 NARRI: 24

column168: On 10/11/2018, at 0012 hours, personnel in the CSXT New Castle Yard discovered GBRX 700594, a loaded tank car of Petroleum Crude Oil, leaking from protective housing. The car was isolated and the shipper, National Response Center, and Pennsylvania Department of Environmental Protection were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2018-1011-00023. Specialized Professional Services, Inc., a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the vapor line valve in the open position and no secondary closure installed. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's contact, Mr. Nate Wiley, phone 972-735-3369. Contractor personnel closed the valve, secured the secondary closure and cleaned all impacted surfaces. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.   Cause Code: 380 NARRI: 80

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: On 10/26/2018 At 0937 ET ERTS was contacted by Austin Spets with XPO Logistics regarding a spill. It was reported that 2 Cups of UN2735 MasterRoc MP 355 1K Accelerator was released from (1) 5- gallon jerry can onto the trailer floor , due to a nail puncture. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and they felt comfortable cleaning the release with the proper PPE. The released product and damaged  jerry can was placed into (1) 95-gallon plastic drum and staged in OS&D for disposal.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: At 1940 ET ERTS was contacted by Griselda Romero with Road Runner Transportation System  regarding as pill. It was reported that 1 cup of UN1760 sodium Hydroxide was released from (1) 3000  pound Plastic tote onto the trailer floor at Bowen Transportation System , due to improper loading.  ERTS dispatched H20 Environmental to manage and clean the release, they generated (1) 5-gallon pail after cleaning the top of the tote placing the pail in their OS&D for disposal .

At 2339 ET ERTS was contacted by Timothy Woloszyn with XPO Logistics regarding a spill. It was  reported that 20 ounces of UN1789 Oakite 32 was released from (1) 20-gallon poly drum onto the  trailer floor, due to improper blocking and bracing causing the drum to fall over. Caller stated that the drum is venting/ smoking and is actively releasing inside the trailer. ERTS dispatched ERS of Indiana- Environmental Remediation Service Inc. to manage and clean up the release. The contractors cleaned  the release and generated (1) 5-gallon Poly pail filled with absorbent and debris that was staged in  OS&D for disposal.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: At 1719 ET ERTS was contacted by Nick Menzo with XPO Logistics regarding a spill. It was reported that 8 ounces of UN3288 NCM 622/64 Precursor was released from (1) 15-gallon fiberboard drum onto the  trailer floor, due to improper loading. Due to the hazardous class being a 6.1 , ERTS dispatched Sunpro  to manage and clean the release. The contractor arrived on site and confirmed 8 ounces were released  , they cleaned the release and generated (1) 55-gallon Poly Drum and staged in OS&D for disposal .

column168: Package was found at an outbound slide and was inspected and opened by Security GSI officer.  GSI Employee #5053526 brought package to the DG office. The package had been opened and had a fuel odor. The GSI officer said they opened, inspected and cleaned up the fluid which had leaked from package. They brought the open package and absorbent pads to our office. Upon our inspection we found that the package contained an aircraft main engine fuel pump. It was apparently wrapped in a plastic bag but it is undetermined if there was any absorbent in the package originally. There is an FAA Form 8130-3 which noted tHis component has been primed and inhibited and is NOT considered dangerous goods. The package does have a strong odor of Jet A. There were no external markings, labeling, shipping papers, emergency response info or other indicators to lead us to believe the contents could be regulated. The shipment was held pending an FAA inspection. FAA PH Is Ryan Pohlke & Steven Redeker were notified electronically.

column168: Our driver attempted to avoid a rear end collision which resulted in the cargo tank trailer initiating a jack knife.  The left side of the cargo tank collided with the rear right corner of a cargo van trailer.  This resulted in a rupture of the cargo tank shell.  Approximately 6000 gallons of product was released from the cargo tank.  Approximately 600 gallons of the product entered a storm drain system exiting into Hogans Creek.  Spill booms and pads were deployed to contain the product.  The remaining product collected in a open swell ditch.  A vacuum truck was used to recover all free product.     Our emergency response contractor worked to mitigate further impact to the environment at the time of the release.  Extensive remediation activities commenced the following day with the oversight of the Florida Department of Environmental Protection and the city of Jacksonville Environmental Department.
column169: FRTL will review defensive driving and driving in adverse weather skills with drivers.

column168: At 0318 ET, ERTS was notified by Ryan Mclean of XPO Logistics, XKC of a release of UN3264-Corrosive liquid, acidic, inorganic, n.o.s. "Hydrex 2849". column168: At 0016 ERTS was notified by Les Ballard of XPO terminal NMP about a cargo release. It was reported that due to improper loading a 30 gallon battery of UN2794, batteries wet, filled with acid, was found on its side having released approximately 1 gallon of material to the trailer floor. Caller stated that a majority of what had released was already dry. Caller additionally stated that the battery in question has been righted and the release was stopped. ERTS went over the SDS with the caller and determined that a contractor needed to be called due to the lack of neutralizer being at the terminal, size of the release, and to resecure the impacted battery. ERTS dispatched Hepaco to clean up all of the released material and neutralize impacted surfaces. The contractor utilized sodium bicarbonate to neutralize the released material. Contractor used a 55 gallon poly drum to overpack the battery and a 55 gallon poly drum to overpack all of the impacted sodium bicarbonate and debris. There were no soils, drains, or waterways impacted by the release. There is no further cleanup needed.

column168: Truck was travelling north on SR 18 in the area of MM  21.8 in the left lane.  Truck ran off the road to the left, entering grass median with driver side front & rear axles.  Vehicle reentered the SR 18 north, proceeded to cross both lanes of the highway and entered the right shoulder.  The tire marks at the scene show the vehicle went into as slide and proceeded to overturn multiple times, striking the guardrail.  The 2800 gallon fuel tank was ripped from the truck and the rear axle also separated from the truck.   The fuel tank ruptured in several places and remaining contents of fuel tank were released onto the ground.   Police responded to the scene. The DEP was notified and also responded to the scene.  ACV Environmental performed the remediation and clean up of fuel spill.

10/31/2018, at 1004 hours, personnel in the CSXT Greenwich yard discovered TILX302282, a loaded tank car of Liquefied Petroleum Gas, leaking from the protective housing area. The car was isolated and Blue Racer Midstream LLC Philadelphia Fire Department Pennsylvania EMA and NRC were notified.  (CHEMTREC 2018-1031-001111. HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the tank car was leaking from the protective housing area. Upon cutting the security seal and accessing the protective housing it was fond that the liquid line valve was open and the secondary securement plug was uninstalled. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Jane Corley 304-455-4102. Contractor personnel closed the liquid line valve and installed the secondary plug. The leak was secured and the car was released to transportation. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1.   Cause Code: 119 NARRI: 75

column168: Original comments:  Package was unloaded from the trailer and transported to the van line via tugger cart. Upon arrival and being placed on the belt the package was found to be wet. QA was radioed and the packaged was retrieved by QA personnel who placed the item in a plastic bin.   The package itself is still intact, though it had become wet due to the leak. Its likely that the package had been leaking for some period of time as the lid only appeared to loose enough to allow for a slow leak. The ethanol bottle was surrounded by air bladders, but the top and bottom had nothing over/under them. The cap being unguarded likely contributed to it coming loose.  The package was immediately brought to QA in a plastic been once the QAstaff was notified about the package. The item was opened upon arrival to inspectand the cap was tightened to prevent any further, inadvertent leaks.  New Comments:

column168: On October 12, 2018, the listed unit was reported actively leaking by your assigned driver at San Bernardino IBU. The exterior inspection revealed a liquid material emitting from underneath the container over the landing gear. The interior inspection revealed mixed containers of acetone containers and a 55 gallon drums of hazmat secured with void filler and Ty Gard at the rear of the load. The drums were found stowed in 2, 2 pattern against the walls in a single layer. Patriot Environmental was dispatched to remediate the leak at our facility. The leak material was determined to a hazmat Acetone emitting from one (1) steel 55 gallon drum. Patriot determined the leak was caused due to a damage and bent ring at the bottom of a 55 gallon drum. Damage to the drum most likely occurred prior to loading at origin. The leaking drum lost approximately 10 gallons; drum was over packed and disposed of by Patriot Environmental.
column169: Shipper should ensure that drums are adequate for transportation and that the load is properly secured to prevent damage to containers while in transit.

column168: Delivery driver failed to properly lock down hose fitting to the tank drop tube, causing it to pop off when he began the flow of product from the trailer.  He immediately shut the valve on the trailer when he saw the fitting pop off.  Approximately 20 gals of 87 grade gasoline was accidentally released onto the parking lot surface.  The driver immediately got the store spill kit and protected the storm drains with spill booms, along with containing the release area with spill booms.   local fire department and our environmental team was contacted for clean up. The release time was only a few seconds until the flow of product was shut off at the trailer valve.

column168: At 1348 ET, ERTS was notified by XPO (USB terminal) regarding a cargo release. According to the caller, approximately 1-lb. of UN 3378, Sodium carbonate peroxyhydrate, "GreenClean® PRO", 5.1, II released from a (1) 50-lb. plastic bag due to improper loading. The caller indicated the release was contained to the trailer floor. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and determined the release could be cleaned using a sweeper and PPE, and containerized into a (1) 5-gallon poly drum to be staged in OS&D. There were no drains, soils or waterways reported to have been impacted by the release.

column168: The shipment was found due to a very strong odor and wet stain on the box. Upon opening the package we found four glass four liter glass bottles. Each bottle was in divided injection foam molded quadrants. There were screw on caps. The screw on caps had a security ring but failed to provide Positive Closure in violation of 49CFR 173.27(d).Two of the screw on caps were loose to the point that would allow the liquid to bounce up to the threads and let gravity take over. The bouncing was due likely to vibration on the aircraft. The freight was held pending an FAA inspection. MEM SECFO Hazmat Manager Stan Satchell& FedEx FAA PHIs Ryan Pohlke& Steve Redeker were notified electronically.

column168: Veolia picked up the shipment from UPS on 10/23/18 and parked it in Veolia's 10 day in-transit transfer  location. column168: Package was received at our shipping dock from a customer with a cockpit voice/data recorder(CVR) inside the package. The 90 day beacon on the CVR contains 1.75g lithium metal content so this was a lithium metal battery packaged in equipment shipment. Package had no markings that it was a dangerous goods/hazardous materials shipment. Our shipping department personnel unpackaged the unit and delivered the unit to our repair department. We notified the shipper they shipped a dangerous good without the proper labels and documentation and that they needed to remedy this in the future and that Universal Avionics was required to report the incident. There was no release.
column169: Our personnel have received training on recognizing hazardous materials arriving at our dock with issues and to notify management when an incident occurs. We provided additional training to recognize when a hazardous material arrives without the appropriate markings or documentation and no release and to immediately report it to management so we can capture all the appropriate information in order to report the incident. We have also notified customers and dealers through newsletters, a notice on our customer website and a service bulletin about reshipping this particular product for repairs and the need to ship as dangerous goods/hazardous material.

column168: On October 29, 2018, at 1222 ERTS was contacted by Salvador Canas of Trimac US to report a tanker release. It was reported an unknown amount of UN2031 Nitric Acid released from a tanker to asphalt below. The amount released and cause is unknown. ERTS dispatched USES for cleanup and transfer operations. At 1415 ET, contractor arrived onsite. Contractor stated apparent leak is coming from behind the jacket. AT 1635 ET, transfer of the product from the tanker was completed. 2000 ET, contractor advised that the new tanker is off site, they were currently monitoring a small drip coming from the jacket of the trailer. They caught the drip in plastic containers. The impacted asphalt and soil was remediated. Contractor used a lime and water solution to neutralize the impacted asphalt and collected liquids with absorbent materials. The impacted asphalt area was 20' x 30' and the dimensions of excavation was 2' x 3' and 2' deep. All soil and absorbent waste was containerized in three 55 gallon poly drums.  1702 ET, Contractor indicated that all the impacted insulation has been removed from the tanker at this time.  1757 EST, Contractor had finished strapping down the jacket on the trailer and let the driver know they were complete with the trailer. 1808 EST, Contractor is off site.

column168: ECLX 16126 was reportedly dripping from bottom outlet cap assembly in the BNSF railyard in Pasco, WA.  BNSF responder investigated and found the top operated bottom outlet valve to be open 2 1/2 full turns.  Valve was closed and outlet cap assembly was removed to examine valve.  No additional leak. No other defects noted, car was secured and released to destination.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: On October 30, 2018 at approximately 1900 hours, a Mechanical Car Inspector at Conrail's Port Reading Yard, Port Reading, New Jersey, reported that PROX 44241, a loaded tank car of UN 1268, Petroleum  Distillates (Natural Gasoline) was leaking from the bottom outlet valve. The tank car was isolated and  the shipper NGL Supply Wholesale (Centennial Energy),  were notified via Chemtrec, report #  2018-10-30-00323. Conrail Hazardous Material Manager, Joe Caccamo along with Hepaco, a Conrail  response contractor, was dispatched to the Port Reading Yard and found a slow drip from the threads  above the bell housing cap below the internal valve. There was no less than tool tight condition found  and it appeared to be a valve issue.  The valve was an updated DOT 117 with disengaging handle. After further inspection it appeared that the  valve was not in a fully closed position as the valve stem nut was not against the stopping point. The nut  was turned with a wrench to  close the approximate remaining 10 degrees. After the valve appeared fully  closed the bell housing assembly was removed and the content of product was drained into a spill pan. After further inspection a small amount of product was still dripping past the internal ball valve and  could not be stopped completely. The Shipper Representative, Brent Foster (720) 317-7145 was made  aware that a transfer would be required.The tank car was re-secured and a spill catch pan was used  to capture any leakage in case the piping below the valve was to fill and leak again.  The transfer of the contents took place on Monday, November 5, 2018 without incident and the contents  of PROX 44241 were transferred into UTLX 212953. The Shipper was notified that a One Time Movement Approval (OTMA) category 1 would be required before transportation to Home Shop could be performed.  Cause Code: 707 NARRI: 2x(5+5+0)x(2+0) = 40

column168: Cargo tank motor vehicle was travelling approximately 65mph on straight, level, dry pavement during daylight.  Driver became distracted with fatigue and dozed.  Vehicle veered towards right side edge of roadway and sideswiped guardrail.  At the end of guardrail, vehicle veered sharply to the right and left paved roadway.  Vehicle overturned as it rotated to the left.  Approximately 413 gallons of gasoline product leaked through tear on the shell.  The product was contained on the ground near the leak.  The product and contaminated earth was removed and replaced.  First responders closed the roadway for approximately 8 hours while the product and vehicle was removed from the scene.
column169: The product was properly contained in a transport vehicle.  The company continues to monitor hours of service activity to discourage fatigued driving.  The drivers are repeatedly reminded during monthly safety meetings and one on one discussions about the dangers of distracted driving.

column168: On 10/26/2018, a Lykins Oil Company (Lykins) driver delivered to a new customer at 30 West Main St. Mowrystown, OH 45155. Location of tank was described to Lykins has: 275-gallon tank outside by driveway. Driver made delivery to the only visible outside tank which was located behind the garage. Garage tank was outside near driveway and had an oil line entering the garage. However, this was the incorrect tank. The correct tank was next to driveway and attached to the house in an enclosure. The tank was not visible because it was enclosed by same material as the main house. The tank by the garage had since been not in use. Previously the oil line from the tank had been disconnected on the inside of the garage from a furnace which had been previously removed and the value was left open. The spill occurred from 10/26/18 to 10/27/18, approximately 180 gallons leaked out into the garage. Lykins were made aware of the spill on 10/29/18. Customer stated he had cleaned up the spill and was not worried about any damage to his property. On 10/31/18 Lykins pumped the rest of the product out in the garage tank and assessed the damage. No evidence of the spill was visible outside of the garage. On 11/2/2018 Lykins reported the spill, NRC # 1229242 and Ohio EPA # 1811-EPA-0001993. At 1252 on 11/2/18, Lykins spoke with Ohio EPA and informed them of the situation. On 11/2/18 at approximately 1430, Lykins and Environmental Management Specialists, Inc. and Highland County EMA arrived at the spill location. They assessed the spill and any property damage or environmental concerns. The only evidence of the spill was inside the garage, except for a small area by the garage door in the yard. No other evidence of the spill was observed on the ground anywhere outside the garage. Environmental Management Specialists, Inc. treated the inside of the garage with Micro-Blaze and the surrounding area outside of the garage as a precaution. Lykins spoke with Ohio EPA again at approximately 1515 on 11/2/2018 and informed them of the assessment and what actions were taken. Ohio EPA was okay with the actions and assessment, then, informed Lykins they were going to close the report and no further action is needed.
column169: Lykins reviews all incidents, in order, to determine the root cause, preventability, and what actions, i.e. training or procedures, need to be conducted or implemented so that the incident will not happen again. Lykins is currently conducting the third round of driver safety meetings for the year and is reviewing this incident with them directly. At these meetings we have been emphasizing the importance of detailed descriptions and being cautious as a driver when delivering. If drivers feel uneasy or are unsure about their delivery location and/or oil tank location, they are to immediately call their supervisor/manager to verify the details of this location. Their supervisor/manager can then contact the customer to get more information and inform the driver with the correct detailed directions before the driver begins the process.

column168: DRIVER WAS OFF-LOADING DIESEL AND HAD FINISHED HIS DROP AND CLOSED THE VALVE AT THE TANK ON THE TRAILER. DRIVER DISCONNECTED THE HOSE FROM THE TRAILER AND BEGAN WALKING THE HOSE OUT TO CLEAR THE HOSE FROM ANY PRODUCT. THE OTHER END OF THE HOSE WAS ATTACHED TO THE ELBOW GOING INTO THE GROUND TANK AT THE GAS STATION. WHILE WALKING THE HOSE OUT TO DRAIN IT, THE HOSE CAME OFF OF THE ELBOW CAUSING AN ESTIMATED 5 GALLONS TO SPILL. IT WAS OBSERVED THAT THE HOSE WAS MISSING THE CLAMP THAT GOES AROUND THE END OF THE HOSE AND TIGHTENED THE HOSE TO THE ELBOW. WASHINGTON DOE WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT, REPORT IR#18-3863 AS A SMALL AMOUNT ENTERED A STORM DRAIN. A 3RD PARTY CLEANUP (NRC) WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED AND IDENTIFIED AND RESPONDED AND IDENTIFIED THAT THE SPILL DID NOT ENTER THE STORM DRAIN, JUST A SMALL AMOUNT IN THE CATCH BASIN.
column169: TO PREVENT THIS FORM HAPPENING AGAIN IN THE FUTURE WE HAVE DONE THE FOLLOWING:  1. PROVIDED EXTRA TRAINING TO ALL DRIVERS WITH REGARDS TO EVALUATING THEIR EQUIPMENT AND MAKING SURE THAT ALL HOSES HAVE CLAMPS AND THAT THEY ARE TIGHTENED. 2. ADVISED ALL DRIVERS TO MAKE SURE THEY ALLOW TIME FOR THE HOSE TO DRAIN PRIOR TO DISCONNECTING AND IMMEDIATELY WALKING THE HOSE OUT. 3. ALL MANAGERS AT EACH TERMINAL WERE REQUIRED TO VERIFY ALL HOSES ON TRUCKS AND TRAILERS FOR CLAMPS AND EQUALITY OF THE HOSE.

Original comments:  Package was originally destined for SCHG0608.  Package was delivered then refused by consignee for damage.  SCHG did not complete a DPR. They re-boxed product and sent it back to the original shipper.  Shipper will not accept anything thatis not in original packaging.  Station CRLS0601 changed the return address to theBreinigsville, PA address per shipper request.  Package was sent over the sorterand then arrived at the damage package area in a tote and the entire bottom ofthe box was wet.    Upon inspection, 1 bottle was empty.  The fumes were quiteobnoxious so admins questioned the hazmat status of the product.  An SDS was obtained and section 14 states the DOT requirements as UN1993, Flammable Liquid, N.O.S.(Isopropanol).  The plastic bottles have a very small ORM-D stamp on them.Wedidnot have the original packaging, but a SPIDR search shows the original boxandwecould not see any ORM-D stamp on the box; however, the pictures were notveryclear.  The UN1993 DOT shipping info may be for large quantities andthe 1 Qt bottles could be shipped as an ORM-D.  Either way the product needs tobe containedin adrum.  New Comments:

column58: Bottom Outlet Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve
column62: Defective Component or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: On October 21, 2018 at approximately 1700 hours NATX 300140, outbound load of acetone from ITC/Mitsui, was observed leaking from the bottom outlet valve.  Slick Response and ITC were notified of the incident and both arrived on scene at approximately 1740 hours.  Inspection found that the bottom outlet valve cap was not tool tight and the bottom outlet valve stem and handle assembly would not completely close the valve.  ITC personnel used a wrench on the valve stem to get the valve closed completely, they then tightened the bottom outlet cap to tool tight condition.  The car was set out awaiting OTMA to ITC to have the valve assembly repaired.    OTMA FRA 181018969 was issued on November 28, 2018 and the car was removed from bad order status for movement to ITC for unloading and repairs.
column169: ITC is handling the repairs to the valve stem and handle assembly. They are also reviewing their process for securing the bottom outlet valve cap to ensure the cap is tool tight prior to offering the car for transportation

column168: TRUCK AND TRAILER TRAVELING WEST ON STATE HIGHWAY 38 HIT LARGE BLACK BULL STANDING IN ROAD AT MP 21. TRUCK AND TRAILER ROLLED OFF OF HIGHWAY INTO A DITCH. DRIVER DECLARED DEAD ON SCENE. LARGE BULL DEAD ON SCENE. BULL WAS NOT CONTAINED AS REQUIRED IN THIS AREA OF THE STATE (I.E. IT IS NOT OPEN RANGE). INITIALLY UNKNOWN IF ANY RELEASE OF PRODUCT, AS THE TRUCK GOT CAUGHT UP IN ELECTRICAL WIRING. ONCE THE FIRE DEPARTMENT (SCOTTSBURG) WAS ABLE TO ACCESS THE VEHICLE IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE TANKS WERE RUPTURED AND PRODUCT HAD RELEASED INTO THE DITCH AND SOIL. FIRST STRIKE WAS DISPATCHED IMMEDIATELY TO THE SCENE, BOOMS WERE PLACED AROUND THE SCENE AND IN THE UMPQUA RIVER (ABOUT 1/4 MILE FROM CRASH SITE). SOURCE EXCAVATION COMMENCED. APPROX. 800 GALLONS WERE RECOVERED FROM THE WRECKAGE AND THE REAMING PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. NO PRODUCT DETECTED IN GROUNDWATER OR SURFACE WATER.
column169: INSTALL CATTLE GUARDS ON ALL VEHICLES TRAVELING IN REMOTE LOCATIONS. LOCAL AUTHORITIES SHOULD BE REQUIRED TO INSURE THAT ALL LIVESTOCK IN FENCED AND CONTAINED. IN OPEN RANGE AREAS, WARNING SIGNS SHOULD BE POSTED.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis
